00:10:28,369 --> 00:10:29,049
it's also out of bounds.

313
00:10:29,049 --> 00:10:30,209
and it can't move any further.

314
00:10:30,209 --> 00:10:31,240
So, it changes.

315
00:10:31,240 --> 00:10:33,280
So, if my stride is two,

316
00:10:33,280 --> 00:10:34,780
it becomes a 2x2.

317
00:10:34,780 --> 00:10:36,120
That's quite a significant reduction.

318
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:36,740
Right?

319
00:10:36,740 --> 00:10:38,200
But for a 5x5 image,

320
00:10:38,200 --> 00:10:39,640
it will also become 2 by 2.

321
00:10:39,640 --> 00:10:41,820
Because it can't move any further outside the original bounds.

322
00:10:41,820 --> 00:10:46,170
So, we see that my stride can also change its dimensions.

323
00:10:46,370 --> 00:10:47,930
But of course, for convolutional layers in general,

324
00:10:47,930 --> 00:10:49,330
our stride is set to one.

325
00:10:49,330 --> 00:10:50,850
This is to get a more complete picture.

326
00:10:50,850 --> 00:10:53,710
It's generally in the pooling layer that we'll set it to two.

327
00:10:53,710 --> 00:10:55,110
And the next thing is padding.

328
00:10:55,110 --> 00:10:56,630
So, what's padding for?

329
00:10:56,630 --> 00:10:58,210
to solve the problem we just mentioned.

330
00:10:58,210 --> 00:10:59,390
So every time I perform a scan,

331
00:10:59,390 --> 00:11:01,320
it's now shrunk to a 6x6.

332
00:11:01,320 --> 00:11:02,900
and it gets scanned down to 4x4.

333
00:11:02,900 --> 00:11:05,060
So, to keep our dimensions the same size,

334
00:11:05,060 --> 00:11:07,240
This is to ensure that the computation remains stable.

335
00:11:07,240 --> 00:11:08,560
So, before we start this scanning process,

336
00:11:08,560 --> 00:11:10,780
we can add a border of zeros around the edges of the image.

337
00:11:10,780 --> 00:11:12,380
So, after adding this zero-padding,

